{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01QzEAZ5MqmV1axuXz46T2Hg","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Demo Design — One Skill, Two Agent Frameworks, Real LLM Synthesis\n2\t\n3\t## Goal\n4\t\n5\tProve the `nvidia-kaggle-skill` is genuinely runtime-portable by driving it\n6\tfrom **both** major agent frameworks present in this environment — **Claude\n7\tCode (Claude Agent framework)** and **OpenAI Codex** — where in each case the\n8\tLLM agent:\n9\t\n10\t1. Loads the skill, and\n11\t2. Runs the deterministic data-gathering workflow (`generate_briefing.py`), then\n12\t3. **Synthesizes** the result into an LLM-written \"Key Strategies\" executive\n13\t   summary — the part that showcases the model, not just our glue code.\n14\t\n15\tOne skill. Two frameworks. Real LLM output. Same verifier over both.\n16\t\n17\t## Environment (verified, not assumed)\n18\t\n19\t| Component | Reality in this env |\n20\t|---|---|\n21\t| `claude` CLI | Claude Code 2.1.175 — headless via `claude -p`, skill-aware |\n22\t| `codex` CLI | codex-cli 0.139.0 — headless via `codex exec`, skill-aware |\n23\t| Codex model | **NVIDIA Inference API, `gpt-5.5`** (`~/.codex/config.toml`); `/nvidia-kaggle` already `trust_level = \"trusted\"` |\n24\t| Claude auth | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` set |\n25\t| Codex auth | `NVIDIA_INFERENCE_KEY` set (provider `nvidia`) |\n26\t| Kaggle | `KAGGLE_API_TOKEN` in `/nvidia-kaggle/.env` |\n27\t| Skill dirs | Codex discovers `~/.codex/skills/`; Claude discovers `.claude/skills/` and `--plugin-dir` |\n28\t\n29\tBoth frameworks are **natively skill-aware** — so the demo is \"the framework\n30\tloads and drives the skill,\" not \"we hand-wrote a tool loop.\" Stronger claim.\n31\t\n32\t## Architecture\n33\t\n34\t```\n35\t                    skills/nvidia-kaggle-skill/  (source of truth)\n36\t                    ├─ generate_briefing.py   --json   ← (1) deterministic data\n37\t                    ├─ synthesize.py\n38\t                    │    ├─ build_synthesis_prompt(briefing) -> str   ← (2) shared prompt, pure\n39\t                    │    └─ synthesize(briefing, provider=…) -> str   ← deterministic fallback\n40\t                    └─ verify_synthesis(text, briefing_json) -> [violation]  ← (3) the gate\n41\t                                        │\n42\t                 ┌──────────────────────┴──────────────────────┐\n43\t        Claude Code harness                          OpenAI Codex harness\n44\t   (claude -p, points at skill,              (codex exec, points at skill,\n45\t    runs briefing + synthesis)                runs briefing + synthesis)\n46\t                 └──────────────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n47\t                              verify_synthesis() over BOTH outputs\n48\t```\n49\t\n50\t**The only shared reasoning artifact is the prompt** (`build_synthesis_prompt`).\n51\tEach framework runs that prompt through *its own* model loop. Neither harness\n52\tduplicates logic; both are thin.\n53\t\n54\t## Build order (layers)\n55\t\n56\tLayers 1–3 are framework-independent and already greenlit / in progress.\n57\t\n58\t1. **`generate_briefing.py --json`** — emit structured tiers. The JSON's\n59\t   closed-class fields ARE the verifier allow-list:\n60\t   `{competition_slug, kernels:[{ref,…}], discussions:[{author,title}], writeups:[{team,rank,url}]}`\n61\t2. **`build_synthesis_prompt(briefing) -> str`** — pure, no API call,\n62\t   unit-tested. Single source of the synthesis instruction.\n63\t3. **`verify_synthesis(text, briefing_json) -> [violation]`** — the gate:\n64\t   - section header present, non-empty, within length bounds → exact\n65\t   - **anti-hallucination (closed-class only):** kernel refs (`owner/slug`),\n66\t     competition slug, and verbatim-quoted handles in the synthesis must be a\n67\t     subset of the JSON entity sets. Free prose / domain vocab NOT asserted —\n68\t     precision over recall.\n69\t   - no leaked page chrome → reuse `support/page_text` patterns.\n70\t4. **Two thin harnesses (this layer needs the keys — now unblocked):**\n71\t   - **Claude:** `claude -p \"<prompt that says: run generate_briefing.py for\n72\t     <slug>, then write a Key Strategies summary>\"` with skill exposed via\n73\t     `--plugin-dir`/`.claude/skills`, `--add-dir /nvidia-kaggle`,\n74\t     `--allowedTools` scoped to Bash(python …)+Read, model pinned.\n75\t   - **Codex:** `codex exec --skip-git-repo-check -C /nvidia-kaggle\n76\t     -o summary.md \"<same task prompt>\"` with skill in `~/.codex/skills/`,\n77\t     sandbox `workspace-write`. Uses NVIDIA `gpt-5.5`.\n78\t   - Each harness is a small `run.sh` (or one `run_demo.sh --runtime claude|codex`).\n79\t\n80\t## Demo deliverable\n81\t\n82\t`demo/competition-intel-briefing/` gains:\n83\t- `run_demo.sh --runtime claude|codex <slug>` — runs the chosen framework\n84\t  end-to-end, writes `<slug>_briefing.md` + `<slug>_strategies_<runtime>.md`.\n85\t- `README.md` updated: the one-skill-two-runtimes story + sample outputs from\n86\t  both frameworks side by side.\n87\t- Sample artifacts from both runtimes committed.\n88\t\n89\t## Verification contract (how we sign off non-deterministic output)\n90\t\n91\t- **Deterministic parts** (1–3): gated exactly like everything else this\n92\t  session — unit tests + `verify_synthesis` returning zero violations across\n93\t  repeated runs.\n94\t- **The synthesis itself** (non-deterministic): gated by *invariants* via\n95\t  `verify_synthesis` (header/length exact, entity set-membership, chrome) +\n96\t  one eyeball pass. No exact-match gate. Run on BOTH runtimes' outputs.\n97\t- Reviewer owns the gate assertions; runs them over Claude and Codex output\n98\t  identically. A real fabricated `owner/slug` ref fails the gate on either.\n99\t\n100\t## Open risks / to verify during build\n101\t\n102\t- Exact headless flags for skill exposure differ per CLI — confirm each CLI\n103\t  actually invokes our skill (not just answers from general knowledge) with a\n104\t  smoke test before relying on it.\n105\t- Codex `gpt-5.5` via NVIDIA API: confirm it can run local python + write the\n106\t  output file under `workspace-write`.\n107\t- Model-id pinning: Claude side pin an explicit model id; Codex uses the\n108\t  configured `gpt-5.5`. Don't hardcode date-suffixed ids.\n109\t- Keep live Kaggle calls bounded (use `--skip-writeups` or cached tiers) so a\n110\t  stage run is fast and not rate-limited.\n111\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ce49b5d9-c28b-4f85-a726-a149698c21ff","uuid":"d9650955-dadb-47eb-87ef-0f3dc6982d6a","timestamp":"2026-06-13T00:31:45.615Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/nvidia-kaggle/demo/competition-intel-briefing/DESIGN.md","content":"# Demo Design — One Skill, Two Agent Frameworks, Real LLM Synthesis\n\n## Goal\n\nProve the `nvidia-kaggle-skill` is genuinely runtime-portable by driving it\nfrom **both** major agent frameworks present in this environment — **Claude\nCode (Claude Agent framework)** and **OpenAI Codex** — where in each case the\nLLM agent:\n\n1. Loads the skill, and\n2. Runs the deterministic data-gathering workflow (`generate_briefing.py`), then\n3. **Synthesizes** the result into an LLM-written \"Key Strategies\" executive\n   summary — the part that showcases the model, not just our glue code.\n\nOne skill. Two frameworks. Real LLM output. Same verifier over both.\n\n## Environment (verified, not assumed)\n\n| Component | Reality in this env |\n|---|---|\n| `claude` CLI | Claude Code 2.1.175 — headless via `claude -p`, skill-aware |\n| `codex` CLI | codex-cli 0.139.0 — headless via `codex exec`, skill-aware |\n| Codex model | **NVIDIA Inference API, `gpt-5.5`** (`~/.codex/config.toml`); `/nvidia-kaggle` already `trust_level = \"trusted\"` |\n| Claude auth | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` set |\n| Codex auth | `NVIDIA_INFERENCE_KEY` set (provider `nvidia`) |\n| Kaggle | `KAGGLE_API_TOKEN` in `/nvidia-kaggle/.env` |\n| Skill dirs | Codex discovers `~/.codex/skills/`; Claude discovers `.claude/skills/` and `--plugin-dir` |\n\nBoth frameworks are **natively skill-aware** — so the demo is \"the framework\nloads and drives the skill,\" not \"we hand-wrote a tool loop.\" Stronger claim.\n\n## Architecture\n\n```\n                    skills/nvidia-kaggle-skill/  (source of truth)\n                    ├─ generate_briefing.py   --json   ← (1) deterministic data\n                    ├─ synthesize.py\n                    │    ├─ build_synthesis_prompt(briefing) -> str   ← (2) shared prompt, pure\n                    │    └─ synthesize(briefing, provider=…) -> str   ← deterministic fallback\n                    └─ verify_synthesis(text, briefing_json) -> [violation]  ← (3) the gate\n                                        │\n                 ┌──────────────────────┴──────────────────────┐\n        Claude Code harness                          OpenAI Codex harness\n   (claude -p, points at skill,              (codex exec, points at skill,\n    runs briefing + synthesis)                runs briefing + synthesis)\n                 └──────────────────────┬──────────────────────┘\n                              verify_synthesis() over BOTH outputs\n```\n\n**The only shared reasoning artifact is the prompt** (`build_synthesis_prompt`).\nEach framework runs that prompt through *its own* model loop. Neither harness\nduplicates logic; both are thin.\n\n## Build order (layers)\n\nLayers 1–3 are framework-independent and already greenlit / in progress.\n\n1. **`generate_briefing.py --json`** — emit structured tiers. The JSON's\n   closed-class fields ARE the verifier allow-list:\n   `{competition_slug, kernels:[{ref,…}], discussions:[{author,title}], writeups:[{team,rank,url}]}`\n2. **`build_synthesis_prompt(briefing) -> str`** — pure, no API call,\n   unit-tested. Single source of the synthesis instruction.\n3. **`verify_synthesis(text, briefing_json) -> [violation]`** — the gate:\n   - section header present, non-empty, within length bounds → exact\n   - **anti-hallucination (closed-class only):** kernel refs (`owner/slug`),\n     competition slug, and verbatim-quoted handles in the synthesis must be a\n     subset of the JSON entity sets. Free prose / domain vocab NOT asserted —\n     precision over recall.\n   - no leaked page chrome → reuse `support/page_text` patterns.\n4. **Two thin harnesses (this layer needs the keys — now unblocked):**\n   - **Claude:** `claude -p \"<prompt that says: run generate_briefing.py for\n     <slug>, then write a Key Strategies summary>\"` with skill exposed via\n     `--plugin-dir`/`.claude/skills`, `--add-dir /nvidia-kaggle`,\n     `--allowedTools` scoped to Bash(python …)+Read, model pinned.\n   - **Codex:** `codex exec --skip-git-repo-check -C /nvidia-kaggle\n     -o summary.md \"<same task prompt>\"` with skill in `~/.codex/skills/`,\n     sandbox `workspace-write`. Uses NVIDIA `gpt-5.5`.\n   - Each harness is a small `run.sh` (or one `run_demo.sh --runtime claude|codex`).\n\n## Demo deliverable\n\n`demo/competition-intel-briefing/` gains:\n- `run_demo.sh --runtime claude|codex <slug>` — runs the chosen framework\n  end-to-end, writes `<slug>_briefing.md` + `<slug>_strategies_<runtime>.md`.\n- `README.md` updated: the one-skill-two-runtimes story + sample outputs from\n  both frameworks side by side.\n- Sample artifacts from both runtimes committed.\n\n## Verification contract (how we sign off non-deterministic output)\n\n- **Deterministic parts** (1–3): gated exactly like everything else this\n  session — unit tests + `verify_synthesis` returning zero violations across\n  repeated runs.\n- **The synthesis itself** (non-deterministic): gated by *invariants* via\n  `verify_synthesis` (header/length exact, entity set-membership, chrome) +\n  one eyeball pass. No exact-match gate. Run on BOTH runtimes' outputs.\n- Reviewer owns the gate assertions; runs them over Claude and Codex output\n  identically. A real fabricated `owner/slug` ref fails the gate on either.\n\n## Open risks / to verify during build\n\n- Exact headless flags for skill exposure differ per CLI — confirm each CLI\n  actually invokes our skill (not just answers from general knowledge) with a\n  smoke test before relying on it.\n- Codex `gpt-5.5` via NVIDIA API: confirm it can run local python + write the\n  output file under `workspace-write`.\n- Model-id pinning: Claude side pin an explicit model id; Codex uses the\n  configured `gpt-5.5`. Don't hardcode date-suffixed ids.\n- Keep live Kaggle calls bounded (use `--skip-writeups` or cached tiers) so a\n  stage run is fast and not rate-limited.\n","numLines":111,"startLine":1,"totalLines":111}}}
